  "latex": "\\frac{d}{dx}[e^x] = e^x, \\quad \\frac{d}{dx}[\\ln x] = \\frac{1}{x}, \\quad \\frac{d}{dx}[\\sin x] = \\cos x",
  "explanation": "Memorizing common derivative patterns saves time: e^x stays e^x, ln(x) becomes 1/x, sin becomes cos, cos becomes -sin. For polynomials, use the power rule mentally: bring down exponent, reduce by 1. Recognizing these patterns eliminates the need to derive from first principles each time.",
  "examples": [
    {
      "problem": "Quick derivative: d/dx(5x³)",
      "solution": "15x²",
      "steps": [
        "Bring down 3, multiply by 5: 3 × 5 = 15",
        "Reduce exponent: 3 - 1 = 2",
        "Result: 15x²"
      ]
    },
    {
      "problem": "Quick derivative: d/dx(e^x + sin x)",
      "solution": "e^x + cos x",
      "steps": [
        "e^x derivative = e^x",
        "sin x derivative = cos x",
        "Sum: e^x + cos x"
      ]
    },
    {
      "problem": "Quick derivative: d/dx(ln x + x²)",
      "solution": "1/x + 2x",
      "steps": [
        "ln x derivative = 1/x",
        "x² derivative = 2x",
        "Sum: 1/x + 2x"
      ]
    }
  ],
